Because we use the projects to manage our unapproved change requests/requirements, I need the ability to migrate approved requests/requirements over to our development project at the point where we have received said approval. I'd like to keep a copy of the original issue in both places so that our project mgrs can track the issue in their project and our developers can track the issue separately in their project (they may want to change the issue type, priority, etc).  

Would like to have the ability to make updates to the issue appear on both copies or on just one copy. 

Would like to keep this separate from moving, which causes the issue to lose its original numbering and which takes it completely out of a project, or linking, which simply links related/duplicated issues.

Currently, the error reporting reports that a particular value "is not in the list of options" - but it does not mention *what* value it thinks is not in the list.

Change 
if (!validOption)
    action.addError(paramName, "The value specified is not in the list of options.");


if (!validOption)
    action.addError(paramName, "The value specified, \" + paramValue + "\",is not in the list of options.");

If the action is invoked via the WEB UI, this is unlikely to occur (unless an administrator edits the fields after the CreateIssueDetails page has been rendered - possible) but when driving it from Jelly or SOAP, it has every likelihood of happenning.

-Nick

Use javascript to lower-case the username on the login submit.

While most people are familiar with case sensitivity - many users arent (esp windows users) - and we have people reporting login problems - but the only problem is that they are using uppercase letters in their username.

It would save us a lot of time if we could do this.

Something like

function CheckForm(form) {

	var bSubmit = false;

	if ( form.USER.value == "" ){
			alert( "Please enter your username." );
			form.USER.focus();
			bSubmit = false;
	}
	else {
			var Username = form.USER.value;
			form.USER.value = Username.toLowerCase();
			//form.submit();
			bSubmit = true;
	}

	return bSubmit;
}

